<paragraph id="8BB40E2E6E7C4078FF485D5615A39DB5" blockId="17.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis id="B97FD23C6E7C4078FF485D5615149E77" bold="true" box="[199,537,332,357]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Comparisons and Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C0B75AD6E7C4078FDAD5D5715FE9E76" authorityName=": Mayer" authorityYear="1974" box="[546,755,333,356]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrops">
<emphasis id="B97FD23C6E7C4078FDAD5D5715FE9E76" box="[546,755,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Epigonus macrops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique in the genus in having a ventral luminous organ; one of the eight pyloric caeca appears to have become modified into this organ. The luminescent window is located mid-ventrally between the anterior part of the pelvic-fins and is covered by a single large scale (see 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A73DF6E7C4078FA845D8F12959EBE" box="[1291,1432,404,429]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref20071" refString="Mayer, G. F. (1974) A revision of the cardinalfish genus Epigonus (Perciformes, Apogonidae), with descriptions of two new species. Bulletin Museum of Comparative Zoology, 146, 147 - 203." type="journal article">Mayer 1974</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 7; Okamoto 
<emphasis id="B97FD23C6E7C4078FEDF5DA3168F9EC2" box="[336,386,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">et al</emphasis>
. 2012: fig. 3). Also, the eighth dorsal-fin spine is isolated between the first and second dorsal fins or, rarely, is connected by a membrane to the seventh spine of the first dorsal fin (expressed as VII-I-I, 10 or 
<collectionCode id="ED1A96EB6E7C4078FF185E1A17D09D05" box="[151,221,512,535]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">VIII-I</collectionCode>
, 10). This feature is shared with only four other species in the genus and is known as a unique diagnostic character for the 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B75AD6E7C4078FED35E3F16FE9D2E" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1810" box="[348,499,548,572]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="telescopus">
<emphasis id="B97FD23C6E7C4078FED35E3F16FE9D2E" box="[348,499,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">E. telescopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A73DF6E7C4078FDC15E3E14009D2F" box="[590,781,548,573]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref21172" refString="Okamoto, M. (2016 b) Epigonidae. In: Matsuura, K. &amp; Hoshino, K. (Eds.), Fishes Collected from the Western South Indian Ocean. Marine Fisheries Research and Development Center, Fisheries Research Agency, Yokohama, pp. 74 - 77." type="book chapter">Okamoto 2016b</bibRefCitation>
). Although several authors reported 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B75AD6E7C4078FB3F5E3F123D9D2E" authorityName=": Mayer" authorityYear="1974" box="[1200,1328,549,572]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Epigonidae" genus="Epigonus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrops">
<emphasis id="B97FD23C6E7C4078FB3F5E3F123D9D2E" box="[1200,1328,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">E. macrops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the east coast of Africa (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A73DF6E7C4078FE0C5E52151C9D72" box="[387,529,584,608]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref20071" refString="Mayer, G. F. (1974) A revision of the cardinalfish genus Epigonus (Perciformes, Apogonidae), with descriptions of two new species. Bulletin Museum of Comparative Zoology, 146, 147 - 203." type="journal article">Mayer 1974</bibRefCitation>
; Shchelbachev 1987; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A73DF6E7C4078FC865E5D14BA9D72" box="[777,951,583,608]" pageId="17" pageNumber="278" refId="ref17192" refString="Abramov, A. A. (1992) Species composition and distribution of Epigonus (Epigonidae) in the world ocean. Journal of Ichthyology, 32, 94 - 108." type="journal article">Abramov 1992</bibRefCitation>
), these authors did not provide any data of the examined specimens (spots of the species in 
<figureCitation id="133012AB6E7C4078FD585E7614109D96" box="[727,797,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[376,1217,1316,1962]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[346,1242,1316,1975]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution of four species of the Epigonus oligolepis group and the E. telescopus group in the Western Indian Ocean." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1182169/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
based on their studies). We thus did not examine any specimens from the 
<collectingRegion id="49CFC0CC6E7C4078FEF65E8A16D99DB5" box="[377,468,656,679]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Western" pageId="17" pageNumber="278">Western</collectingRegion>
Indian Ocean area.
</paragraph>
